<DOC><DOCNO> AP880917-0002 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0246EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Rebels     09-17 0444</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Colombia-Rebels,0458</SECOND><HEAD>Guerrillas free five imprisoned comrades, kill hostage</HEAD><BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Left-wing guerrillas firing automaticweapons burst into a federal court building in the town of BugaFriday and freed five of their comrades being held for trial,police reported.   They said a judge's administrative assistant was taken hostageby the gunmen and his body was found with a bullet in the headbeside a highway near the town 160 miles southwest of Bogota.   Two of the guerrillas freed by the attackers were captured afteran hour-long pursuit, the police said. They did not report anyother casualties or give further details.   In other developments, leftist rebels freed 22 governmentsoldiers and policemen captured in a raid last month and alsoreleased two Colombian geologists seized in another attack, thegovernment and military announced.   The soldiers and policemen freed Friday had been taken prisonerAug. 23 by guerrillas of the People's Liberation Army and theColombian Revolutionary Armed Forces during a joint attack on thenorthwestern town of Saiza.   A statement from the office of President Virgilio Barcos said aone-day cease-fire had been arranged so the captives could bereleased in the Uraba region, about 300 miles northwest of Bogota.   Two of the government troopers had been wounded in the rocketand mortar attack on the police station in Saiza, Gen. Jesus Ariassaid in an interview with the radio station RCN. He did not listtheir conditions or elaborate.   The two geologists released Thursday were among five who workedwith coal companies and were kidnapped Aug. 20 by rebels of anotherguerrilla group, the National Liberation Army, or ELN.   Rebels freed the two geologists in an arranged meeting with agroup of reporters in the city of Bucaramanga, 200 miles northeastof Bogota.   An ELN communique said the three other geologists would bereleased soon, but declared the guerrillas would launch anoffensive against foreign coal-mining companies.   Exxon and the Colombian state company Carbacol are partners in a$3 billion surface mine near Colombia's Caribbean coast.   ELN guerrillas have attacked oil pipelines and oil installationsoperated by Occidental Petroleum Co., Shell Oil and the Colombianstate company Ecopetrol 46 times this year, according to thegovernment. It placed the damage at $300 million.   A Defense Ministry communique released Friday said 1,174 peoplehave been killed this year in guerrilla attacks and battles betweenrebels and security forces.   It listed the slain as 499 guerrillas, 378 civilians and 297policemen and soldiers.   The ministry has reported 2,037 people were killed last year infighting involving rebels, government forces and civilians caughtin the violence.</TEXT></DOC>